<Content>Great budget choice Hotel Catedral, Mexico CityAugust 2007. We were very pleased 鈥?it is an excellent budget optiMy girlfriend and I stayed at Hotel Catedral for a week at the end of on in a prime location near the Zocalo and the main tourist sites. Our room did not have a fridge, which was a pain, and the view could hardly have been worse 鈥?the back of some disused building and a car park, but for the price we could not complain. We did not ask to change rooms so I do not know whether an upgrade would have been readily available. The rooms on the top floors might have better views judging from the views from the roof terraces, which are open to all. The bathroom was clean and decent, with a large shower/wet room.The hotel restaurant was as good a place as any in the vicinity for breakfast 鈥?I had the hot cakes (ie US-style pancakes a few times and can鈥檛 complain). Lots of the more traditional Mexican breakfasts (using chilli sauces for example) were not what I was looking for at that time of day, but the hotel鈥檚 range was wide enough to cope. Caf茅 Popular nearby is also fairly decent, with better pastries but the coffee and hot chocolate always came loaded with cinnamon or something similar and wasn鈥檛 to my taste.There was free wi-fi throughout the hotel.If you use Lonely Planet Mexico, like we did, you might find it difficult to locate two restaurants which are supposed to be among the five best in the whole country 鈥?for some reason LP features them in its 鈥榖est of mexico鈥?section at the front of the book but they do not appear in the detailed listings for Mexico City. So no addresses or telephone numbers are provided. Luckily we had some time on our hands and managed to track them down 鈥?they are well worth a visit.In general, the food in Mexico City was nothing to write home about, and even these restaurants would not be regarded as special in the US or the UK, but El Tajin in Coyoac谩n was a very pleasant setting and decent food and Aguila y Sol in Polanco was excellent food and drink in a smart dining room. And compared to the price of the best restaurants in the UK/US, these really are bargains.El Tajin 鈥?Centro Cultural Veracruzano, Miguel Angel de Quevedo 687, Mexico City, Mexico. Miguel Angel de Quevedo is a long main road, and El Tajin is easy to miss 鈥?it is inside an arts centre. Although El Tajin is in Coyoac谩n, it is a long, long way from that metro station, albeit that the (long) walk into the main part of Coyoac谩n and then south through small residential streets is extremely pleasant. Getting a taxi might be a good option. Another option is to bypass Coyoac谩n. Miguel Angel de Quevedo has its own metro stop 鈥?go past Coyoac谩n and Viveros and then you will just have a longish (but not pretty) walk along the main road.Aquila y Sol 鈥?Emilio Castelar 229, Polanco, 11560 Mexico, DF. It has recently moved to this address, so some sources might give its old address on Moliere (which is just around the corner). 
