<Author>AMB&JAS
<Content>隆Excelente! My wife and I stayed at this hotel August 13th-16th, 2007. It was our first stay, but it will not be our last. My wife and I are seasoned visitors to Mexico City, so we knew we wanted security, cleanliness, convenience, courteous service, and the right price, in a hotel. Hotel Catedral delivered in all respects. If anyone wants to visit the Centro Hist贸rico of Mexico City, this hotel is for you. It is also ideal if someone wants to make daytrips to Xochimilco, Teotihuac谩n, Coyoac谩n, etc. There is a travel agency in the lobby, but we did not use it. The hotel restaurant opens at 7:00 a.m., closes at 11:00 p.m., and it serves good, if unspectacular, food. My wife liked the sincronizadas. The bar sells wonderful cubas libres. And, it is not too far to the airport.This hotel does not pile on the amenities. For example, there were no hand or face towels. And it is on a busy street that gets jammed with street vendors in the afternoon. But it did not matter, given all the positives the hotel offered, like a purified water tap in the bathroom, and terraces on the seventh floor. If you stay at this hotel, you may want to eat breakfast at the local branch of Los Bisquets de Obreg贸n, on Calle Tacuba #85, just off the Z贸calo. The caf茅 con leche is wonderful, as are the biscuits with jelly. It opens at 7:30 a.m. Also, be sure to eat dinner at least once at the Caf茅 de Tacuba, at Calle Tacuba #28. My wife found a terrific souvenir shop, Arte Mexicano Para El Mundo, at Monte de Piedad #11.I have visited Mexico City 25-30 times, and I have never been a victim of a crime. I have never even lost a personal item. So I disagree with the generalization that Mexico City is a crime-infested, violent metropolis. In fact, the only time I have been mugged was in Chicago. But visitors to Mexico City do need to use common sense. Do not flash money or jewelry, know where you are, do not walk around drunk, and keep an eye on your belongings. The population of Mexico City is in the many millions, so the odds and human nature make it likely that more than a few people are dishonest or criminal. But I am convinced that they are a tiny percentage of the population.The hotel staff will call a sitio cab for you, and they are safe. I became friendly with the driver of our first cab, he gave me his cell phone #, and thereafter he drove us everywhere. It was win-win. Once, when he was busy with other passengers, he sent his father, also a cabbie, to drive us to our destination! The only negative is the traffic. It is HORRIBLE, so budget extra time if you will be getting around by car. 
