<Content>Fabulous value for the money (but can be really noisy) The room itself was pretty much on par with a nice Holiday Inn, and there are upgrades that are more spacious than the standard room. The lobby was very nice with a running fountain and marble stairs and looked rather upscale. The staff were all excellent and most spoke very good english - one girl at reception was even a native speaker. The cabbies the hotel called for us were prompt, reasonably priced, safe and trustworthy (one even dropped off a sweater I'd left in his car!) Overall, we were floored at how inexpensive the place was, especially considering that it is in the absolute heart of the historic center, and very easy to access. Also, the restaurant in the lobby is very good for breakfast. Drawbacks - if your room is facing the Zocalo, you could be in for a very noisy night, as Mexican street parties can last into the wee hours, as we just found out. Also, we had to change rooms when a TON of young people (late teens) moved into the hotel for the night and partied with great vigor for hours. The hotel wanted to go tell them to quiet down, but we just said we preferred to change rooms and , luckily, our new room was an upgrade! Despite the noise, I'd definitely go back, as the value is just incredible for the money and, well, location, location, location!Note - the subway is a breeze to use in Mex City, plus it's so cheap it's nearly free. I found the best rate for exchange was at the airport, where you can compare the prices of maybe 12 different exchange booths and pick the best one. The hotel exchange rate, for example, was 11 pesos for a dollar, whereas I got 11.41 at the airport (no commission). However, the hotel rate was STILL far better than my own bank was offering here in California, and the hotel was a very convenient, safe place to exchange money.Finally, there is a FABULOUS Swiss-Italian restaurant in the Zona Rosa, that we highly recommend. The food was awesome and the service and decor were very, very nice. You can feel very comfortable in casual clothes, while still feeling like you're eating out at a quality place. I can't remember the name, but it was listed by name and address only in the cruddy little city guide they hand out at the airport. Good luck finding it, as it was GREAT! 
