<Author>psychtobe
<Content>a real treasure We stayed here in early June for 4 nights. We expected a small but plain hostel-like hotel, but instead got a surprisingly charming and nicely-appointed little gem!The location is superb for those who want to be near the Zocalo. 5 minutes to the Zocalo metro station, and a wonderful view of the rear of the Catedral itself. You are a short walk to all of the major Zocalo attractions inlcuding the plaza, the Palacio nacional, the Templo Mayor, the catedral, and the street markets. The area felt comletely safe to me and my wife, even as late as midnight. There are a surprising number of people around, and activities of all kinds at all hours. We watched a few election rallies in the Plaza, Aztec dancers, street vendors, beggars, etc. The area is a little gritty on some streets, including the street the Hotel is on, so keep that in mind if you want chic surroundings.The lobby is clean and sharp with a lot of marble. There is a small travel agent desk and 2 internet computers (30 pesos/hour). There is a nice fountain in the lobby.The staff was friendly and helpful if not effusively so. I mostly spoke Spanish with them, although several of the staff do speak English. They called cabs for me and pointed me to various restaurants, etc. Gave us a late checkout without resistance, and took care of the bill quickly.We had a junior suite, with king bed and Jacuzzi tub. Again, we got more than we expected. The bed was very firm, possibly too firm for some people鈥檚 liking. There was a bland but serviceable sofa. The TV got about 10 cable channels, including 1-2 in English. The lighting is mostly recessed halogen spotlights. There is a mirrored closet and quite a bit of storage space. There is a safe in the room but it doesn鈥檛 work, you have to use the safe boxes at the front desk. The bathroom was in good condition, and in particular the shower/tub was large, clean, with good water pressure and nice lighting. There is a tap for agua purificada on the vanity.The room was on the interior courtyard, so very quiet. Occasionally we heard a few dishes rattling from the kitchen, but that did not bother us. We slept with the windows open and the fan on and were very comfortable.The room service was unobtrusive and complete. One light bulb went out one day and they changed it that night, without our asking. We left 20-30 pesos daily as a gratuity.There are 2 small terraces on the 7th floor of the hotel, which are beautiful and calm in the evenings. Views of the back of the Catedral as well as of other parts of the city. It鈥檚 not fancy but it was also never crowded. I found it very relaxing.We paid 577 pesos per night, which includes tax and the 10% discount for paying in cash. At the current exchange rate of 11:1, that works out to about 52 dollars per night, an absolute steal in my opinion.Overall, I will definitely be back the next time I go to Mexico City. The only major downsides for some will be the location near the Zocalo (not in a more touristy area). For me that was a major plus, and allowed us to get a cross-section of working class Mexican society. 
